<DOC><DOCNO> AP900723-0228 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-23-90 1019EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet10am     07-23 0279</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0296</SECOND><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The stock market was broadly lower in earlytrading today amid sustained pressure from disappointingsecond-quarter earnings.   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials continued its retreatfrom the 3,000 level, falling 22.28 points to 2,938.86 in the firsthalf hour of trading.   Volume on the Big Board came to 25.32 million shares as of 10a.m. on Wall Street.   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 3 to 1 on theNYSE, with 258 up, 784 down and 458 unchanged.   A flurry of disappointing quarterly earnings reports for thesecond quarter pushed the Dow lower last week, and analystsexpected more bad news to hasten the decline.   McDonald's had not yet opened for trading today after a poorearnings report released late Friday.   Adding to the downward pressure, prices of long-term Treasurybonds fell sharply in early trading after a sharp selloff in Tokyoovernight. Also, traders said there was little incentive to buybonds ahead of the government's monthly budget statement today,which is expected to show a deficit.   The widely watched Dow average, which measure the stock price of30 large industrial companies, last week cracked but failed toclose above the 3,000-point level.   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks wasdown 1.29 to 196.36. The American Stock Exchange composite indexwas 1.71 lower at 358.74.   On Friday the Dow Jones industrial average fell 32.67 to2,961.14, finishing the week with a net loss of 19.06 points.   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 5 to 3 on theNYSE, with 577 up, 904 down and 514 unchanged. Big Board volumetotaled 177.81 million shares.</TEXT></DOC>